{"id":124,"date":"2023-09-21T17:40:06","date_gmt":"2023-09-21T17:40:06","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/?page_id=124"},"modified":"2024-12-18T20:04:41","modified_gmt":"2024-12-18T20:04:41","slug":"research","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/research\/","title":{"rendered":"Research"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Research Philosophy<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">Our approach regards perception and action as two sides of the same coin, expressing a currency which is not the veridical Euclidean representation of the environment. Studying perception is the first step to revealing how visual information is organized to spring action: perception presents actionable space. Our first mission is therefore to study the&nbsp;<em><a href=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/research\/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"124\">visual encoding of 3D object properties<\/a><\/em>. The relationship between visual encoding and the unfolding of a motor action, which requires the same 3D properties, is the aim of our second line of research exploring&nbsp;<em><a href=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/research\/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"124\">visuomotor mapping<\/a><\/em>. We believe that perception and the motor mapping are always synergistically updated. Our third mission is to study the&nbsp;<em><a href=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/research\/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"124\">plasticity of the motor mapping and visual encoding of 3D information<\/a><\/em>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-text-color has-alpha-channel-opacity has-background is-style-dots\" style=\"background-color:#3a6b35;color:#3a6b35\"\/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-group alignwide\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained\">\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Visual encoding of 3D object properties<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-1 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex\">\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"683\" data-id=\"596\" src=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-596\" srcset=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1-300x200.jpg 300w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1-200x133.jpg 200w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1-660x440.jpg 660w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2024\/11\/CoPsy-3DIPA-Lab_4L9A0710-1.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n<\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">How does vision inform the visual system about the three-dimensional structure of the world? What information is important, for a complex organism like human primates, to be able to successfully interact with the surrounding environment?<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">A large community of researchers, spanning psychophysicists, cognitive neuroscientists and neuroscientists, assume that the goal of the visual system is to reconstruct the Euclidean structure of the world. All theoretical and empirical efforts are therefore placed in understanding how the brain achieves this goal. Surprisingly, the Euclidean representation assumption is never a topic for debate.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">We argue that the Euclidean representation of objects is neither the goal of the visual system nor a feature of the perceptual space. Stripping away this hypothesis from the guiding principles of research in human 3D vision, we seek alternative computational models and empirical tests for understanding how the multitude of visual signals shapes our perceptual experience of the 3D world.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">\u2014 Domini, F., Caudek, C. (2013). <a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/chapter\/10.1007\/978-1-4471-5195-1_20\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/chapter\/10.1007\/978-1-4471-5195-1_20\">Perception and Action Without Veridical Metric Reconstruction: An Affine Approach.<\/a> In S J. Dickinson Z. Pizlo (Eds.).&nbsp;<em>Shape Perception in Human and Computer Vision<\/em>&nbsp;(pp. 285-298). Springer London.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p id=\"visuomotor\" style=\"font-size:18px\">\u2014 Domini F, Caudek C.&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/19963200\">Matching perceived depth from disparity and from velocity: Modeling and psychophysics.<\/a>&nbsp;<em>Acta psychologica<\/em>. 2010; 133(1):81-9.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-text-color has-alpha-channel-opacity has-background is-style-dots\" style=\"background-color:#3a6b35;color:#3a6b35\"\/>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Visuomotor mapping<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow\">\n<figure class=\"wp-block-video\"><video crossorigin=\"anonymous\" crossorigin=\"anonymous\" crossorigin=\"anonymous\" height=\"720\" style=\"aspect-ratio: 1280 \/ 720;\" width=\"1280\" autoplay loop muted src=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2023\/09\/home_3.webm\" playsinline><\/video><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:21px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">If the visual system is unable to reconstruct veridical metric properties of the world, how can we grasp objects if we don&#8217;t know their true size and location? Is it possible that perceptual distortions are only found in purely perceptual tasks, made by passive observers viewing a stimulus from a static point of view?<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">In order to address these questions, we built a complex VR environment where observers can interact with objects located within their personal space. In this environment the position of the observer&#8217;s head and their upper limbs are tracked. Observers can make perceptual judgments about virtual objects, and we can study their behavior when they reach for and grasp these objects. In addition, with our system of computer-controlled moving parts that can provide haptic feedback, participants can also feel physical objects when present.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">This sophisticated system allows us to pursue a new line of research in which we study how depth information is used for grasping virtual objects. Instead of only measuring perceptual judgments about the 3D structure of an object, as has been commonly done in the literature, we determine how the aperture between finger and thumb is related to the depth of the object at the end of a grasping action. In recently published studies, we provide converging evidence with the results of visual tasks.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">\u2014 Campagnoli C, Croom S, Domini F.&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/28837967\">Stereovision for action reflects our perceptual experience of distance and depth.<\/a>&nbsp;<em>Journal of vision<\/em>. 2017; 17(9):21.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p id=\"plasticity\" style=\"font-size:18px\">\u2014 Bozzacchi C, Domini F.&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/26269553\">Lack of depth constancy for grasping movements in both virtual and real environments.<\/a>&nbsp;<em>Journal of neurophysiology<\/em>. 2015; 114(4):2242-8.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-text-color has-alpha-channel-opacity has-background is-style-dots\" style=\"background-color:#3a6b35;color:#3a6b35\"\/>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Plasticity of motor mapping and visual encoding of 3D information<\/h2>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"300\" height=\"251\" src=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2023\/09\/Escher-300x251.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-133\" srcset=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2023\/09\/Escher-300x251.jpg 300w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2023\/09\/Escher-768x642.jpg 768w, https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/files\/2023\/09\/Escher.jpg 1000w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" \/><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-small-font-size\">M.C. Escher&#8217;s &#8220;Drawing Hands&#8221; \u00a9 2009 The M.C. Escher Company-Holland<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"height:16px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">Perception and action have been traditionally considered as distinct brain functions. This view took hold following a number of paradoxical dissociations between perception and action in healthy and neurologically impaired individuals. We take a fundamentally different view, proposing that these processes work together to form a coordinated system, wherein perception informs action about the state of the world, and in turn, action signals perception when perception is faulty. We hypothesize that this system works cooperatively, leveraging error signals from sensory feedback when interacting with the environment to modify the state of the motor system when this is sufficient, or to change the very perceptual interpretation itself. While error signals have been studied extensively in the sensorimotor adaptation field, advances made here have yet to be extended in an integrated framework for how perception and action coordinate adaptive behavior.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">This approach brings together two fields &#8211; 3D visual perception and sensorimotor adaptation &#8211; to build a comprehensive framework with the potential to transform current understanding of visually-guided action.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">\u2014 Cesanek E, Domini F.&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.govhttps\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/28958908\">Error correction and spatial generalization in human grasp control.<\/a>&nbsp;<em>Neuropsychologia<\/em>. 2017; 106:112-122.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">\u2014 Cesanek E, Campagnoli C, Taylor JA, Domini F.&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/28853037\">Does visuomotor adaptation contribute to illusion-resistant grasping?<\/a>&nbsp;<em>Psychonomic bulletin &amp; review.<\/em>&nbsp;2017<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">\u2014 Volcic R, Fantoni C, Caudek C, Assad JA, Domini F.&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/24155312\">Visuomotor adaptation changes stereoscopic depth perception and tactile discrimination.<\/a>&nbsp;<em>The Journal of neuroscience: the official journal of the Society for Neuroscience.&nbsp;<\/em>2013; 33(43):17081-8.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Research Philosophy Our approach regards perception and action as two sides of the same coin, expressing a currency which is&hellip; <a class=\"read-more\" href=\"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/research\/\">Read more <span class=\"screen-reader-text\">Research<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":2180,"featured_media":0,"parent":0,"menu_order":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","template":"","meta":{"footnotes":""},"class_list":["post-124","page","type-page","status-publish","hentry"],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/124","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/page"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/2180"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=124"}],"version-history":[{"count":41,"href":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/124\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":666,"href":"https:\/\/sites.brown.edu\/3dipalab\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/124\/revisions\/666"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https